<subsection xml:id="subsec-application-of-the-laws-of-indices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Applications of the laws of indices</title>
    <p>
        Some of the applications are:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Simplifying expressions:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Laws of indices are fundamental for simplifying complex algebraic expressions, making them easier to work with. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Solving for the unknown in equations:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        They are used to solve equations involving exponents, such as exponential equations. 
    </p>
    <p>
       <m>\textbf{ Population growth:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Indices can be used to model population growth and make predictions about future population trends. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Financial calculations:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        They are used in compound interest calculations and other financial applications involving exponential growth. 
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the value of <m>x</m> in:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2^{2x}=16</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3x^2 = 18</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3^{2x-4} = 1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4^{-x} = \frac{1}{16}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To solve for <m>2^{2x}=16</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            First express <m>16</m> as a prime factor in index form
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>16 = 2^4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence, <m>2^{2x} = 2^4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Next we equate the powers:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>2x=4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence, <m>x = 2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                              <m>3x^2 = 18</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Here, we divide both sides by the coefficient of <m>x</m> which is <m>3</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\frac{3x^2}{3} = \frac{18}{3}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>x^2 = 6</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Applying laws of indices we have:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>(x^2)^{1/2}= 6^{1/2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence, <m>x= 6^{1/2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>= \sqrt{6}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m>3^{2x-4} = 1</m> 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            According to definition of zero indices, any number <m> a^0 = 1</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence, 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>3^{2x-4} = 3^0</m> 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since the bases are the same, we equate the powers:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>2x-4 = 0</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>2x=4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>x=2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4^{-x} = \frac{1}{16}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To solve for <m>x</m>, we can write <m>\frac{1}{16}</m> as <m>16^{-1}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            So, <m>4^{-x} = 16^{-1}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Next, we need to express <m>16</m> to be of base <m>4</m> so that both sides have equal bases.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since, <m>16 = 4^2</m> then <m>16^{-1} =(4^2)^{-1}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>(4^2)^{-1}= 4^{2 \times -1} = 4^{-2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now, <m>4^{-x}=4^{-2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           Equating the indices: <m>-x=-2</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>x = 2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
</subsection>